{"questionId":"27479","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Hydrogen and iodine react to form hydrogen iodide.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">H<sub>2</sub> (g) + <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>I</mtext></math><sub>2</sub> (g) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" class=\"wrs_chemistry\"><mo>⇌</mo></math> 2H<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>I</mtext></math> (g)</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider the reaction of hydrogen with solid iodine.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">H<sub>2</sub> (g) + <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>I</mtext></math><sub>2</sub> (s) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" class=\"wrs_chemistry\"><mo>⇌</mo></math> 2H<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>I</mtext></math> (g)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Δ<em>H</em><sup>⦵</sup>&nbsp;= +53.0 kJ mol<sup>−1</sup></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Calculate the Gibbs free energy change, Δ<em>G</em><sup>⦵</sup>, in kJ mol<sup>−1</sup>, for the reaction at 298 K. Use section 1 of the data booklet.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>«Δ<em>G</em><sup>⦵</sup> = 53.0 kJ mol<sup>–1</sup> – (298K × 0.1665 kJ K<sup>–1</sup> mol<sup>–1</sup>) =» 3.4 «kJ mol<sup>–1</sup>» ✔</p>","meta":{"questionId":"27479","referenceCode":"22M.2.hl.TZ2.4d(iii)","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"Calculate the Gibbs free energy change, ΔG⦵, in kJ mol−1, for the reaction at 298 K. Use section 1 of the data booklet.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"d(iii)","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Additional higher level (AHL)","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 15: Energetics/thermochemistry","15.2 Entropy and spontaneity","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 15: Energetics/thermochemistry"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}